1 0 0 1 56 732.0 Tm (Coins, Trust, and Concrete: The Vending Machine Boom in Postwar Japan, 1955-1985) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 718.0 Tm () Tj
/F1 9 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 704.0 Tm (Hiroshi Tanabe and Claire Densmore) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 690.0 Tm (Journal of Economic and Social History, Vol. 43, No. 4 \(2016\) - JID-015) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 676.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 658.0 Tm (Abstract) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 644.0 Tm (Japan became, in three postwar decades, the most vending-machine-dense society on earth.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 630.0 Tm (This paper argues that the boom was not merely a story of technology or affluence but rested) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 616.0 Tm (on a particular configuration of low crime, a convenient coinage, expensive retail labour,) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 602.0 Tm (and dense urban form. By assembling machine-count data against these variables we show that) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 588.0 Tm (the vending machine succeeded where its preconditions coincided, and we use the case to) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 574.0 Tm (argue that consumer technologies diffuse along social rather than purely technical channels.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 560.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 542.0 Tm (Introduction) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 528.0 Tm (An unattended machine that holds both goods and cash on a public street is an act of trust) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 514.0 Tm (as much as a piece of engineering. Postwar Japan filled its streets with such machines to a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 500.0 Tm (degree no other society matched, and the puzzle this paper addresses is why the same) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 486.0 Tm (technology, available everywhere, took root so much more deeply there.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 472.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 458.0 Tm (We argue that the answer lies not in the machines but in their social and economic) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 444.0 Tm (surroundings. The vending machine is a lens through which the distinctive features of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 430.0 Tm (postwar urban Japan come into focus.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 416.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 398.0 Tm (The Preconditions) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 384.0 Tm (Four conditions, we contend, made the boom possible. Low rates of street crime meant a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 370.0 Tm (cash-filled machine could stand unattended overnight without being broken open. A coinage of) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 356.0 Tm (convenient denominations meant common purchases could be made with a coin or two, without) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 342.0 Tm (the friction of notes or change.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 328.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 314.0 Tm (Expensive retail labour, rising with the postwar economy, made the machine an attractive) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 300.0 Tm (substitute for a clerk, while dense urban form guaranteed enough foot traffic past any given) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 286.0 Tm (spot to justify the machine's footprint. Each condition was necessary; together they were) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 272.0 Tm (sufficient.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 258.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 240.0 Tm (Counts Against Conditions) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 226.0 Tm (Assembling regional machine-count data, we found the density of vending machines tracked our) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 212.0 Tm (four preconditions closely. Districts with higher foot traffic and higher labour costs) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 198.0 Tm (carried more machines, and the introduction of a particularly convenient coin denomination) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 184.0 Tm (was followed by a marked acceleration in installations.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 170.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 156.0 Tm (Where any precondition was weak, density lagged. Areas with thinner foot traffic supported) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 142.0 Tm (far fewer machines regardless of affluence, confirming that no single factor drove the boom.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 128.0 Tm (The machine flourished only at the intersection of all four conditions, which is precisely) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 114.0 Tm (why it flourished so unevenly elsewhere in the world.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 100.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 82.0 Tm (Diffusion Along Social Channels) Tj
