/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 736.0 Tm (The broader lesson concerns how consumer technologies spread. The vending machine was not a) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 722.0 Tm (Japanese invention, and nothing about it was technically inaccessible to other wealthy) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 708.0 Tm (societies. Its uneven adoption shows that a technology diffuses not wherever it is available) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 694.0 Tm (but wherever its social preconditions are met.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 680.0 Tm () Tj
1 0 0 1 56 666.0 Tm (Trust, coinage, labour cost, and urban density are not properties of the machine but of the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 652.0 Tm (society around it. The Japanese case demonstrates that to explain why a technology succeeds) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 638.0 Tm (in one place and not another, one must study the place at least as closely as the) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 624.0 Tm (technology.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 610.0 Tm () Tj
/F2 12 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 592.0 Tm (Conclusion) Tj
/F1 10 Tf
1 0 0 1 56 578.0 Tm (Japan's postwar vending-machine boom rested on a coincidence of low crime, convenient) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 564.0 Tm (coinage, costly labour, and urban density rather than on the machine alone. The case shows) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 550.0 Tm (consumer technologies diffusing along social channels, succeeding where their preconditions) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 536.0 Tm (align and faltering where they do not. The unattended machine on the corner is, read) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 522.0 Tm (correctly, a portrait of the society that tolerates it.) Tj
1 0 0 1 56 508.0 Tm () Tj
